text.text: Dojo Has it Large in... Stratford

text.html: Sitting pretty at the end of the Jubilee Line (and some other lines at that), Stratford might seem like a world away to some. East Londoners will tell you that ain’t the case though, and might even mutter something about best ‘til last. The Olympics went down here in a big way in 2012 (just incase you were chilling under a rock) and the area has seen some major love from developers and aspiring independents alike. Worth the Oyster fare? Only one way to find out… gwarn Stratford, let’s have it large!
text.text:
Sitting pretty at the end of the Jubilee Line (and some other lines at that), Stratford might seem like a world away to some. East Londoners will tell you that ain’t the case though, and might even mutter something about best ‘til last. 

The Olympics went down here in a big way in 2012 (just incase you were chilling under a rock) and the area has seen some major love from developers and aspiring independents alike. Worth the Oyster fare? Only one way to find out… gwarn Stratford, let’s have it large!
Best for… getting trollied with the locals in a hella old pub

tip.text:
King Edward VII, or just King Eddie's to affectionate locals, is a properly charming (and equally scruffy) East London drinking hole. A 19th Century Grade II listed building, you can bet your ass these walls have seen some shit. What the pub lacks in visual beauty it makes up in character. You’ll find any number of eclectic Eastenders here throughout the week.

The bar stocks your standard selection of ales and lagers, while there are plenty of mains to be munched here for under a tenner - pies are about £8, while burgers might cost you a bob or so more. Thursday is open mic night, Sunday is the weekly quiz, and Saturday is the home of ‘a spoonful of poison’ - people are invited up to perform whatever they like (no covers and no stripping allowed) - expect the unexpected.

text.text: King Eddie’s has been knocking about since the 19th Century, which means it’s definitely put a shift in to become everyone’s favourite Stratford local. Yeah, it’s pretty scruffy in places but if it ain’t broke, don’t fix it. Right? Right - wet your beak, have a chat with the lovely staff and discover the backyard (pokey but a secret sun trap nevertheless). Appreciate the mural, ask for the corresponding photo and try to spot the difference.
Best for… murals, antipodean mornings and late night hijinks

tip.text:
They’ve been in Dalston since ‘09, and now they’ve set up shop in Stratford’s developing East Village. Tina, We Salute You’s new offering has a flip-side though - their alcohol license means you can get involved in local craft beers and cocktails in the evenings (hurrah!). The daytime vibe is still very much coffee, antipodean brunches (pancakes on the weekend) and fresssshly baked cakes.

We’re big fans of the huge, colourful Tina mural by the kitchen, while cheap Ebay steals prove you don’t have to spend a pretty penny on furniture (the sofa cost a quid). Just like the Dalston spot, the local art on the walls will be changing fairly regularly, and keep your eyes peeled for film and quiz nights. Chefs will be taking up residency in the kitchen here every month or two, so watch this space.

text.text: Tina Stratford and Tina Dalston are sister cafes, except E20’s Tina has a bit more of a wild side - she’s well up for necking cocktails and locally brewed craft beers once the sun goes down. Much funner on the inside than it may seem from without, you can expect an eclectic mix of furniture and art up in here. Resident chefs and changing murals mean you'll never get bored of Tina. Nice one, girl!
Best for… splashing around like it’s no one’s business

tip.text:
You might need a second or two to digest the architectural spectacle that is the London Aquatics Centre, built for the Olympics and every bit the fitting stadia of champions. But you don’t have to be an officially recognised champ to splash around here, with the 50m pool used in the Olympic and Paralympic games open to the public. With ten lanes for swimming, and natural light pouring in through the ceiling, you should have plenty of space to get those arms and legs thrashing.

Specialist sessions such as disability swimming, exercise classes and women’s only swimming are held in the training pool. Test your balance and nerves in an AquaSplash session, where a 20 metre long inflatable course challenges you to overcome it.

Adult: £4.95 (off peak)/ £5.25 (peak)

Child: £2.90 (off peak)/ £2.90 (peak)

Aqua Splash: £5 (child)/ £7.50 (adult)

Off Peak Hours - 9:00am - 5:00pm
Peak Hours - 6:00am - 9:00am & 5:00pm - 10:00pm

text.text: Who doesn’t love a cheeky splash around? We certainly do, especially when Olympic athletes have propelled their limbs through the very same water and chlorine, which is fully the case at the London Aquatics Centre. You don’t build swimming pools this cool for nothing, so while you’re standing outside marvelling at the architectural nous involved in conceiving the structure, don’t forget that you can pop in for a dip too.
Best for… baskin’ and boozin’ in the sunshine

tip.text:
***Permanently Closed***

Lovingly cradled by building sites, The Print House has carved out an idyllic riverside spot amongst the grey of Stratford-in-progress.

The menu consists of solid European classics, presented with more sauce squiggles than an episode of Art Attack. The Flash Fried Sea Bass with Chorizo and Feta mash stole the show, however the Fish & Chips on the table next to us was so majestic, we’d be tempted to recommend it based on this shallow observation alone.

The converted warehouse space is modern, open plan with a hefty dollop of ‘creative type’ atmosphere. We went for a sit-down meal, but the huge outside terrace area makes it a no-brainer for a sunny afternoon tipple, delightfully out of sight of mother Westfield.

Best for… supporting a good cause

tip.text:
This heart-warming social enterprise has a lovely plot in the Olympic Park - you can see the famous rings from where you’re sitting. Actually, you can see a lot from where you’re sitting, mainly because of all the glass involved in this building. High ceilings and skylights only add to the airy feeling of this spacious (but particularly cosy) cafe.

Run by the Camden Society, Unity Kitchen’s profits go towards creating opportunities for young people with learning disabilities - they have apprentices working in the kitchens and have even gone on to employ former apprentices in part-time roles. Coffee comes from Climpson and Sons, while food offerings include daily soup specials, lasagnas, freshly made cakes and sandwiches. Beware the school trips.

text.text: There’s a lot to admire about the project here at Unity Kitchen, one of the few London venues managed by The Camden Society, who work tirelessly to create opportunities for people with disabilities. Apprentices work in the kitchens to prepare themselves for further work (which this social enterprise helps them find): the lovely chap who served us our brownie here was a former apprentice and is now employed in the cafe part-time. Expect smiles, floods of natural light and cheap chow.
Best for… a square meal and a stiff drink

tip.text:
The interior might be straight outta Brooklyn but the Darkhorse culinary palette is firmly Modern-European. Energy efficiency and sustainability are high on these chaps’ agendas - everything is cooked on coal in a Berther oven and produce comes from this neck of the woods.

We totally dig the sound of the Bertha roasted onglet steak & bone marrow with watercress salad. More than a restaurant though, Darkhorse also bills itself as a cocktail bar and wine cave - expect organic and biodynamic wines to wash your food down with, while a classic cocktail probably seems fitting for post-meal sipping. You’d be wise to book Thursday through to Sunday.

text.text: 1 cocktail guy, 1 food guy. When 2 experts come together it’s usually something to get a bit excited about: Ian and Lee’s Darkhorse project sets out to combine the best of both worlds in a sexy, industrial setting in Stratford’s burgeoning East Village. Expect seasonal, fresh dishes at all times - the menu is written off the back of what’s available and ripe. Sustainable produce; cooking on charcoal; biodynamic wines - these lot are definitely doing their bit for the ol’ planet.
Best for... a doughtastic voyage

tip.text:
Alberto’s artisan bakery demonstrates a true passion for bread-making - this lot work tirelessly in the kitchen, experimenting with shapes and flavours, always trying to better themselves. They’ve managed to knock out a bread that consists of five different seeds and four different flours. We didn’t even know that was a thing.

As you can image the menu here is doughcentric and mediterranean-inspired: sandwiches, cakes and tarts feature as well as more basic breakfasts of granola and toast etc. The Signorelli interior was designed by Alberto’s partner, and creates a lived-in, cosy feel in a light, Nordic space. You’ll find Alberto selling his focaccia on Fridays at the market in St. Paul’s (with a smile on his face).

text.text: Signorelli’s Alberto had a huge smile on his face when he told us about his nutella biscuits - he can often hear the kids running through the housing units towards his bakery shouting about them. This artisan bakery is all about passion, love for bread making and a determination to experiment; all born from a genuine desire to please people. As a hangout it’s airy and cosy, decorated with bits and bobs from Alberto’s past homes - well, well worth a visit.
Best for…crazily creative cakes

tip.text: Drinks in jam jars, payments taken in BitCoin, crazily creative cakes - this outrageously on-trend cafe is well worth the minute stroll from Stratford. This haunt is home to some bare good vibes, and its home-baked tarts, quiches, breads and freshly ground coffee will undoubtedly make Sawmill a regular lunchtime hangout for all you East London heads.

tip.text:
If anyone's got their fingers in all the pies, it's got to be The Wanstead Tap - cafe, bar, bottle shop, cinema and performance space, it's really got it all. But, but, but - THE BEERS. Prepare for a mind-boggling selection of craft beers, from local and nationwide brewers alike, completely dominating the far wall.

Pair a pint with one of their smoked venison and cheese toasties (bread comes from Bread Ahead in Borough Market) or any of their other interesting bar snacks and you'll be laughing. Everything's sourced locally so yes, this is a community hotspot. Check their website for regular music, comedy and all sorts of other live entertainment happenings.

text.text: So this is a bit naughty of us, as Wanstead isn’t strictly speaking Stratford - but hey, we’re explorers and it’s only a stone’s throw away so ssshh. You could walk these streets for days without stumbling across this gem at the end of a quiet, residential street. You’re not ready for the beer selection. We repeat: you are not ready. Extensive is an understatement - there’s a bloody gluten-free section!
